==Service history==
[[File:SMS Kaiser Max illustration.tif|thumb|Illustration of ''Kaiser Max'', c. 1866]]

During the [[Second Schleswig War]] of 1864, ''Don Juan d'Austria'' was deployed with the [[ship of the line]] {{SMS|Kaiser|1858|2}} and two other vessels to the [[North Sea]], but arrived too late to take part in any fighting, then-Commodore [[Wilhelm von Tegetthoff]] having already inflicted a strategic defeat on the Danish squadron at the [[Battle of Heligoland (1864)|Battle of Heligoland]].<ref>Greene & Massignani, p. 210–211</ref> All three ships saw action during the [[Seven Weeks' War]] that pitted Austria against Prussia and Italy two years later. The war at sea culminated at the [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]] in July 1866, where all three ships were heavily engaged, though they were not seriously damaged and inflicted little on their Italian opponents. Neither side's ships carried guns strong enough to defeat their opponents armor plating.<ref>Wilson, pp. 242–245</ref> After the war, the ships were disarmed and [[:wikt:laid up|laid up]].<ref>Sondhaus, p. 8</ref>

In 1867, the ships were drydocked to correct some of their handling deficiencies,<ref name=G268/> and install their new rifled guns.<ref>Sondhaus, p. 10</ref> They did not return to active service after the work was completed, however. Severely reduced naval budgets owing to Hungarian disinterest&mdash;the Austrian Empire having been replaced by the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire|Dual Monarchy]] in the postwar ''[[Ausgleich]]''&mdash;in naval matters prevented the Austro-Hungarian fleet from taking an active policy.<ref>Gardiner, p. 267</ref><ref>Sondhaus, pp. 40–41</ref> As the ships were badly rotted and thoroughly obsolete by the early 1870s, Rear Admiral [[Friedrich von Pöck]], then the commander of the fleet, proposed that the ships be "rebuilt". The ships were in fact stricken from the [[naval register]] in 1873 and [[ship breaking|broken up]] for scrap, but the subterfuge allowed Pöck to build three new ships, also named {{SMS|Kaiser Max|1875|2}}, {{SMS|Don Juan d'Austria|1875|2}}, and {{SMS|Prinz Eugen|1877|2}}, during a period where parliament steadfastly refused to approve funding for new ironclads. Some parts of the ships were reused, to include the engines but not the boilers, armor plate, and other miscellaneous equipment to save construction costs.<ref>Gardiner, pp. 268, 270</ref><ref>Sondhaus, pp. 45–46</ref>

